The latest project, Inrupt, is a company building on Berners-Lee's open source platform Solid.
At Solid, users can choose where to store their data and which people have access to the information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee said that the purpose is ‘world domination’.
"We have to do it now," he said about the start-up.
‘It is a historic moment’.
The app uses Solid's technology to let people create their own 'personal online data storage' or a POD.
It may include contact lists, work lists, calendars, music libraries and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify all are available on one browser at a time.
What's unique about the personal repository online is that it's completely up to the user who should have access to that type of information.
The company calls it ‘personal data authorisation’.
The idea behind Inrupt is according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, that the company should provide resources, process and relevant competence to make Solid accessible to all.
The company consists in the moment of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some leased developers to work with the project and a bunch of volunteer programmers.
From this week on, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team don't talk to «Facebook and Google that they're going to introduce something completely new or not, which will make their business models completely recalibrated overnight.
«We do not ask for their authorisation».
In an article on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's mission is to offer commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps to protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid."
In 1994 Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he established the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an important voice in the debate on online neutrality.
Although he launches Inrupt, Berners-Lee will still be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely optimistic about the next era of the web," added Berners-Lee.
