Germany’s new warship delayed once again
The newest frigate of the German Navy would have been completed in 2014 to replace old warships from the cold days of the war, but this will not happen until the earliest next year due to failing systems and galloping costs, reported local media.
The completion of the ‘Rheinland-Pfalz’, the mastership of the completely new frigates in the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, which quoted a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to have survived the marine in 2014, but the major problems after delivery were pursued by the ambitious project.
The four ships in the Baden-Wuerttemberg class ordered the marine completely back in 2007 will replace the old frigates in the Bremen class.
They are agreed to be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles and some stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important characteristics include longer maintenance periods – it should be possible to apply the most recent frigates for up to two years away from the port of origin.
However, still delays mean that the advanced warships – they were said to give Germany strength in the sea – will already be out of date before they are put into service, reports Die Zeit.
The fateful F125 friar made headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss yard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the marine has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media mentioned a number of important ‘software and hardware defects’ that rendered the warship useless in a combat mission.
Software defects were particularly important since ships in the Baden-Wuerttemberg class are to be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors - only half of the crew of older frigates in the Bremen class.
It was also revealed that the ship has a huge overweight, which reduces performance and limits its ability to perform upgrades in the future.
The 7000-tonne heavy "Rheinland-Pfalz" is estimated to be twice as heavy as similar ships of the same class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to defective hardware, the price tag of the entire project – including training for the crew – has begun to become a problem.
It is claimed to have reached staggering EUR 3.1 billion – from the original EUR 2.2 billion.
The problems surrounding the new frigates are particularly important in the light of fresh warnings that Germany's marine strength is shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, the head of the German Government’s Defence Committee, confirmed that the marine is actually ‘empty for usable ships’.
The official said that the problem has escalated over time because old ships were out of line, but there was no new vessel.
He regrets that none of the frigates in the Baden-Wuerttemberg class could be used by the marine.
National Trust Watches on the Secret Life of Flag Museums
New research carried out at a landing point in the Scottish Highlands shall reveal how bats use the landscape of the hunt for food.
There is hope that the findings will shed light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and help to design future conservation measures.
The study for researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brittle and water flag mouse at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special callers will be located at major locations around the property to track bat activity through the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
The sound analyses of all recordings by experts will determine the frequency of the bats and the species doing what.
A habitat map and a report will then be drawn up to provide a detailed landscape view of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Adviser, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will be included in the decision on the measures to be taken, such as the installation of pasture land and the best management of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has sunk considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction affecting breeding sites and habitat degradation.
Windmills and lighting may also present a risk, same with fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials and assaults from house taxes.
You know, bats aren't really blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes for catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and roadside obstructions when they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten competent experts who regularly carry out surveys, surveys of breeding sites and, among others, rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only own bat reserve at the Three Landersandem in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here on Threeave we have a perfect area for bats," he says.
"We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive."
He underlines the importance of mapping the bats before carrying out maintenance on a property since the accidental destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young people, and perhaps destroy an entire local population.
Flag mouse is protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or disturb them or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish employee of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the audience to help in the work.
She says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we just don't know how the populations are doing."
