"We need an agreement," said Clark.
The Japanese car manufacturer said that the consequences of delayed border crossing in case of a non-contractual Brexit could mean fewer jobs.
The Burnaston plant — producing Toyotas Auris and Avensis — produced almost 150,000 cars last year, of which 90 % was exported to the rest of the EU.
‘If the United Kingdom leaves the EU at the end of March, we will, in my view, experience that production at our factory stops,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s Managing Director at Burnaston.
Other British producers have raised concerns about leaving the EU without agreement on how cross-border trade will work, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
For example, BMW says that they will close the Mini factory at Oxford for a month after Brexit.
The main concern is about what the car manufacturers say is supply chain risks for any Brexit without agreement.
Toyota’s production line is operated on the basis of “order as needed” and parts arrive every 37 minutes from suppliers both in the United Kingdom and the EU for cars made on-demand.
If the United Kingdom leaves the EU without an agreement on 29 March, the border may remain, which is what industry says may lead to delays and a lack of parts.
It will be impossible for Toyota to keep more than one day's inventories at the Derbyshire factory, said the company, and thus the production will stop.
Clark said that Theresa May’s Brexit plan for further relations with the EU is ‘presisted to avoid such border controls’.
"We need an agreement; we want to get the best deal that makes us, as I say, not only enjoy success at the moment, but that we seize this opportunity," he said on the BBC Radio 4's Today program.
‘The message, not only from Toyota but also from other car manufacturers, is that we must be able to continue absolutely what has been a very successful set of supply chains’.
Toyota could not say how long production will be stopped but cautioned that increased costs in the long term will reduce the competitiveness of the factory and eventually lead to job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked in Burnaston for 24 years and is a trade union leader at the factory, said that the members are becoming increasingly concerned: ‘My experience suggests that when these jobs disappear, they will never come back’.
